## <a id='install-login'></a>Step 2: Install the cf CLI ##

The `cf` CLI is your primary tool for deploying and managing your applications.

1. Click [Tools](https://console.run.pivotal.io/tools) on the left navigation menu of the Developer Console to access the Tools page.

1. Install the appropriate `cf` CLI version for your OS.
1. Run `cf help` to confirm that the tool is installed correctly.
The example shows the beginning lines of output for this command.

<pre class=”terminal”>
$ cf help
NAME:
   cf - A command line tool to interact with Cloud Foundry

USAGE:
   [environment variables] cf [global options] command [arguments...] [command options] 
...
</pre>


## <a id='connect-api'></a>Step 3: Connect to PWS Using the Cloud Foundry Public API ##

This step targets the Cloud Foundry public API endpoint `api.run.pivotal.io` and establishes your connection to PWS.

1. Run `cf login -a api.run.pivotal.io`

1. Enter the email and password that you established in Step 1.

The example shows the output of this command. When your account contains only a single org and space, PWS automatically targets them. Otherwise, PWS prompts you to select an org and space.

<pre class=”terminal”>
$ cf login -a api.run.pivotal.io

API endpoint: https://api.run.pivotal.io

Email> joeclouduser@acme.com

Password> 
Authenticating...
OK

Targeted org Cloud-Apps

Targeted space development


                   
API endpoint:   https://api.run.pivotal.io (API version: 2.8.0)   
User:           joeclouduser@acme.com   
Org:            Cloud-Apps   
Space:          development  
</pre>

You are now ready to deploy applications.

